For the last year, the SEC has waged war on crypto and destroyed billions of dollars of value

In the last 2 weeks, the Courts called BS in the Ripple case and the House Financial Committee just passed bipartisan crypto legislation that would enable a sane regulatory framework for the ecosystem to grow

But the fight is just beginning

The bill still needs to pass the full House vote (this fall), then Senate, and then Exec. Many of these people are still under the Warren spell, openly hostile to crypto, and need to hear from their constituents why they should protect and support it.

Amazingly enough, phone calls and emails to congressmen go a long way here. We’ve seen contacts from constituents flip congressmen from hostile or ambivalent to strongly supportive.

It might be the most important thing we can do to help crypto grow and achieve its potential to create economic freedom in the world.

You're building an app and can use:

1. Privy, et al that enable a simple, segregated wallet for your app alone

2. Single sign-on w/ unified wallet that enables users to bring their assets/identity everywhere

Assume for a moment they both offer seamless UX w/o janky app-switching, gas fees, etc.

Which do you choose?
That's right. #2 would probably look more like single sign-on with Google but it would be a self-custody wallet.

Right. It would be kind of like having individual email address/password signups for all the different sites/apps you use. All relevant, useful, segregated to that individual app, but not portable or interoperable to others.

This would kind of mirror the web2 approach - you can create your AirBnB username/password that is dedicated and segregated, but you can also login with Google to use a unified identity. A lot of differences under the hood, but definitely some precedents for that approach.

The Visa / Mastercard swipe fee settlement is estimated to save retailers $30B

Moving onchain will save them 50x more - $1.5T+ 👇

After decades of regulatory pressure, industry lobbying, class-action suits, etc - retailers were able to get swipe fees reduced from roughly 2.5% to 2.45% on average

That reduction is estimated to save retailers $30B in fees and considered a big win for the industry

But transactions on Base today cost 0.03% - nearly 100x lower than the new swipe fees - and are still getting cheaper!

So while retailers may save $30B from the current settlement reducing swipe fees by 4-7 bps, they still have another $1.5T to save by moving onchain

We now know the limits of what’s possible with the existing system, even through decades of litigation and regulatory pressure.

Time to update it, onchain.
